1 SENATE FLOOR VERSION
February 23, 2026
2
3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR
4 SENATE BILL NO. 683 By: Paxton and Seifried
5
6
7 An Act relating to education; amending Section 2,
Chapter 278, O.S.L. 2023, as last amended by Section
8 2, Chapter 295, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025,
Section 28-101), which relates to the Oklahoma
9 Parental Choice Tax Credit Act; modifying definition;
expanding qualifying expenses eligible for credit;
10 requiring submission of receipt or list to claim
certain qualifying expenses; prohibiting taxpayer
11 from claiming multiple authorized credits for the
same eligible student; expanding authority to conduct
12 audit for qualifying expense claims; modifying
certain reporting requirements; updating statutory
13 language; and providing an effective date.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY Section 2, Chapter 278, O.S.L.
18 2023, as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 295, O.S.L. 2025 (70
19 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 28-101), is amended to read as follows:
20 Section 28-101. A. As used in the Oklahoma Parental Choice Tax
21 Credit Act:
22 1. “Accrediting association” means a recognized legal entity
23 that meets the accreditation requirements set by the State Board of
24 Education, another accrediting association approved by the State
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB683 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 Boar d of Education, or a legal entity that accredits education
2 organizations in multiple states, whose purpose is to verify that an
3 education program meets or exceeds predetermined criteria, and
4 monitor the education organization during the time it is accredited
5 by completing regular reevaluations and on-site inspections of the
6 education program;
7 2. “Commission” means the Oklahoma Tax Commission;
8 3. “Curriculum” means a complete course of study for a
9 particular content area or grade level;
10 4. “Department” means the State Department of Education;
11 5. “Education service provider” means a person, business,
12 public school district, public charter school, magnet school, or
13 organization that provides educational goods and/or or services to
14 eligible students in this state;
15 6. “Eligible student” means a resident of this state who is
16 eligible to enroll in a public school in this state. Eligible
17 student shall include a student who is enrolled in and attends or is
18 expected to enroll in a private school in this state accredited by
19 the State Board of Education or another accrediting association or a
20 student who is educated pursuant to the other means of education
21 exception provided for in subsection A of Section 10-105 of this
22 title;
23 7. “Qualified expense” for the purpose of claiming the credit
24 authorized by paragraph 1 of subsection C of this section means
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB683 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 tuit ion and fees at a private school in this state accredited by the
2 State Board of Education or another accrediting association. Such
3 private school shall comply with the provisions of subsection L of
4 this section. Provided, the amount of tuition and fees considered a
5 qualified expense pursuant to this paragraph shall not include
6 tuition and fees paid with any scholarship or tuition and fees
7 discounted or otherwise reduced by the school. For the purpose of
8 claiming the credit authorized by paragraph 1 of subsection C of
9 this section and for eligible students enrolled or expected to
10 enroll in a private school in this state, qualified expenses also
11 include the following:
12 a. tuition and fees for learning programs, including
13 summer learning programs,
14 b. academic tutoring services provided by an individual
15 or a private academic tutoring facility,
16 c. textbooks, curriculum, or other instructional
17 materials including, but not limited to, supplemental
18 materials or associated online instruction required by
19 an education service provider,
20 d. fees for nationally standardized assessments
21 including, but not limited to, assessments used to
22 determine college admission and advanced placement
23 examinations as well as tuition and fees for tutoring
24 or preparatory courses for the assessments, and
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB683 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 e. online educational programs;
2 8. “Qualified expense” for the purpose of claiming the credit
3 authorized by paragraph 2 of subsection C of this section means the
4 following expenditures:
5 a. tuition and fees for nonpublic learning programs,
6 online or in person,
7 b. academic tutoring services provided by an individual
8 or a private academic tutoring facility,
9 c. textbooks, curriculum, or other instructional
10 materials including, but not limited to, supplemental
11 materials or associated online instruction required by
12 an education service provider, and
13 d. fees for nationally standardized assessments
14 including, but not limited to, assessments used to
15 determine college admission and advanced placement
16 examinations as well as tuition and fees for tutoring
17 or preparatory courses for the assessments; and
18 9. “Taxpayer” means a biological or adoptive parent,
19 grandparent, aunt, uncle, legal guardian, custodian, or other person
20 with legal authority to act on behalf of an eligible student.
21 B. There is hereby created the Oklahoma Parental Choice Tax
22 Credit Program to provide an income tax credit to a taxpayer for
23 qualified expenses to support the education of eligible students in
24 this state.
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB683 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 C. For the tax year 2024 and subsequent tax years, and fiscal
2 year 2026 and subsequent fiscal years, there shall be allowed
3 against the tax imposed by Section 2355 of Title 68 of the Oklahoma
4 Statutes a credit for any Oklahoma taxpayer who incurs a qualified
5 expense on behalf of an eligible student, to be administered subject
6 to the following amounts:
7 1. If the eligible student attends a private school in this
8 state accredited by the State Board of Education or another
9 accrediting association or claims any other qualified expense, as
10 defined in paragraph 7 of subsection A of this section, the annual
11 maximum credit amount for tax year 2024, fiscal year 2026, and each
12 subsequent fiscal year shall be:
13 a. Seven Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($7,500.00) or the
14 amount of tuition and fees for the private school,
15 whichever is less, if the combined adjusted gross
16 income of the parents or legal guardians of the
17 eligible student during the second preceding tax year
18 does not exceed Seventy-five Thousand Dollars
19 ($75,000.00),
20 b. Seven Thousand Dollars ($7,000.00) or the amount of
21 tuition and fees for the private school, whichever is
22 less, if the combined adjusted gross income of the
23 parents or legal guardians of the eligible student
24 during the second preceding tax year is more than
