16 educate the eligible student at the private school, whichever is
17 less;
18 4. If the eligible student attends a private school in this
19 state, accredited by the State Board of Education or another
20 accrediting association, that primarily serves financially
21 disadvantaged students, the credit amount shall be the maximum
22 credit amount authorized by paragraph 1 of this subsection or the
23 amount of the cost to educate the eligible student at the private
24 school, whichever is less. The cost to educate the eligible student
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB683 SFLR Page 7
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 shal l be equal to the average cost to educate all students attending
2 the private school, which shall be calculated by dividing the
3 private school’s total expenditures in the previous year by the
4 total enrollment in the previous school year. A private school
5 shall be deemed to be primarily serving financially disadvantaged
6 students if ninety percent (90%) of the private school’s admissions
7 are based on enrolling students whose gross family income is two
8 hundred fifty percent (250%) of the federal poverty threshold or
9 below;
10 5. The taxpayer shall retain all receipts of qualified expenses
11 as proof of the amounts paid each tax year the credit is claimed and
12 shall submit them to the Commission upon request;
13 6. If the credit exceeds the tax imposed by Section 2355 of
14 Title 68 of the Oklahoma Statutes, the excess amount shall be
15 refunded to the taxpayer; and
16 7. Credits claimed by a taxpayer pursuant to the provisions of
17 this section shall not be used to offset or pay the following:
18 a. delinquent tax liability,
19 b. accrued penalty or interest from the failure to file a
20 report or return,
21 c. accrued penalty or interest from the failure to pay a
22 state tax within the statutory period allowed for its
23 payment,
24
